{
  "corpus_id": "smoke_v0",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "split": "smoke",
  "base_robot_count": 4,
  "shared_scenario_defaults": {
    "note": "All six maps share these values so cross-map comparisons isolate map geometry, not scenario setup. Values match SimulationConfig's own defaults (robotics_sim/simulation/config.py) -- nothing here was invented.",
    "world_bounds": { "x_min": -10.0, "x_max": 10.0, "y_min": -8.0, "y_max": 8.0 },
    "grid_resolution": 0.5,
    "body_radius": 0.2,
    "safety_radius": 0.35,
    "vision": 2.5,
    "vision_model": "LiDAR",
    "camera_fov_degrees": 70.0,
    "robot_start_positions": [
      { "x": -8.6, "y": -6.6 },
      { "x": -7.4, "y": -6.6 },
      { "x": -8.6, "y": -5.4 },
      { "x": -7.4, "y": -5.4 }
    ]
  },
  "format_notes": [
    "The .sim schema (robotics_sim/simulation/config.py: config_to_sim_payload/config_from_sim_payload) has no field for fire placement, no seed field, and its 'world' block is written on save but never read back by the loader -- the runtime always rasterizes ground truth against the fixed WORLD_X_MIN/X_MAX/Y_MIN/Y_MAX constants instead. This corpus does not redesign the .sim format: fire_scenarios and geometry_seed live only in this manifest.",
    "The .sim format's robot/multi_robot blocks do require one scenario's worth of robot start poses to be embedded directly in the .sim file (that is how robotics_sim.simulation.engine spawns robots at runtime, via normalized_robot_start_configs). robot_start_positions is therefore intentionally duplicated between each .sim file and this manifest's shared_scenario_defaults -- not a second, divergent source of truth, just the one the format forces to live in both places. Geometry (bounds, grid_resolution, obstacles) lives only in .sim files, never here."
  ],
  "maps": [
    {
      "map_id": "smoke_v0_01_open",
      "filename": "01_open.sim",
      "family": "open",
      "difficulty": "smoke",
      "geometry_seed": null,
      "robot_start_positions": [
        { "x": -8.6, "y": -6.6 },
        { "x": -7.4, "y": -6.6 },
        { "x": -8.6, "y": -5.4 },
        { "x": -7.4, "y": -5.4 }
